description: Probably from Middle Low German tûte, tǖte (“horn, conical paper bag”), whence also German Tute (“horn, bugle”) and German Tüte (“bag, paper bag”). Compare also Saterland Frisian Tüütje (“paper bag”), West Frisian tút (“spout, toot, kiss”), Dutch tuit (“horn, spout, nozzle”), Swedish tuta (“to honk”), Danish tud (“spout, nozzle”), Old Norse tútna (“to be blown up”). Further origin unknown.

entries.meaning: (logistics) A kind of plastic box used for transporting goods.
examples: They can be used for palleted bags, totes, or bales and can also be used to transport large logs.

verbs.description: tote (third-person singular simple present totes, present participle toting, simple past and past participle toted)

examples: It took ten pallbearers to carry her coffin. There was a picture of them toting it in one of the tabloids.

description: Short for total, with e to distinguish from tot in writing.

verbs.description: tote (third-person singular simple present totes, present participle toting, simple past and past participle toted)

entries.meaning: To add up; to calculate a total.
(Britain, Australia) A pari-mutuel machine; a totalizator.
examples: He was a humorist of note and keen at repartee,
He laid the odds and kept a "tote", whatever that may be,
